        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "https://github.com/cython/cython/blob/d0835eabed53d79134a17959e49e359c19aa31c2/Cython/Utility/CppSupport.cpp#L40-L46\n\nAnything than derives from `std::exception` (and doesn't match anything more specific) should be handled by the `catch (const std::exception& exn) {` case. That does preserve `.what`.\n\nC++ allows you to throw anything though, and not just exception types. So anything handled by `...` is an unknown type that doesn't derive from `std::exception` so I don't think there's a `.what()` to preserve (and we'd still need to know the type to access it)",
            "created_at": "2026-03-20T07:37:19Z",
            "html_url": "https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/3239#issuecomment-4096279930",
